Cicero's anxiety in regard to his own position was somewhat relieved in Sept, 47 ac, by the arrival of Caesar, who generously gave him permission to remain in Italy.⁴ He went almost directly to Rome, and his letters in the main, up to the close of 46 rac, were written either in that city or at his villas at Tusculum and Cumae. The battle of Thapsus was fought Apr. 6, 46 ac„ and by it Caesar’s supremacy in Africa was established3 but the tidings of this important battle and even of the violent deaths⁶ of the Pompeian leaders, Scipio, Petreius, Afranius, and* Juba,⁸ do not seem to have stirred Rome so deeply as the news that Cato had taken his own life at Utica! feeling that the cause of the Republic was beyond hope. The little memoir which Cicero wrote of his personal and political friend⁸ called forth opposition pamphlets from the Caesarians, Hirtius⁹ and Brutus‚¹⁰ and even Caesar found time on the eve of the battle of Munda to write an ‘Anticata’ ¹¹
